My general rule of thumb is to convert the comparator arguments to local (pointer) variables of the correct type, and then use those in the rest of the function.  You can&#39;t index `void *` variables in standard C, regardless of what GCC says.  There isn&#39;t a size for the `void` it points at.


    int cmp(const void *vp1, const void *vp2)
    {
        const char *s1 = *(char **)vp1;
        const char *s2 = *(char **)vp2;

        // Following your code - but it isn&#39;t very meaningful
        printf(&quot;x: %c | y: %c\n&quot;, *s1, *s2);
        printf(&quot;x: %s | y: %s\n&quot;,  s1,  s2);
    
        size_t len = strlen(s1);
        for (size_t i = 0; i &lt; len; i++)
            printf(&quot;x: %c | y: %c\n&quot;, s1[i], s2[i]);
    
        return 0;
    }

That&#39;s a lot easier to understand (and write) than the contortions you were using.  There&#39;s even a moderate chance it would &quot;work&quot;, though since all elements compare equal, the data won&#39;t be sorted in any meaningful way (one of the reasons for the comment in the code).

